{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9ae976da-3059-471f-8de3-8a8030e443dc","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 changed **overload resolution** for extension methods on arrays. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nBecause `T[]` is implicitly convertible to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, the span overload is a \"better\" match under the new rules. But `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be represented in expression trees or handled by the expression interpreter, so `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)` throws at runtime.\n\n## How to fix\n\nForce the compiler back to the `Enumerable` overload by removing the array-to-span conversion from consideration. Either **cast to `IEnumerable<int>`** or **call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly**:\n\n**Option A — cast the receiver:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — static call:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth ensure the compiler picks the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3315ef85-23fa-43f2-936a-d18396e9f95a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about this. In .NET 10 / C# 14, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces a new extension member syntax, and more relevantly, the way `Enumerable.Contains()` resolves for arrays may have changed.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The key issue is likely related to how `.Contains()` on arrays is resolved. \n\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, calling `.Contains()` on an `int[]` array resolves to the `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>` extension method. But in .NET 10, the resolution might have shifted — possibly to a new overload or to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead, which could affect how the expression tree compiles and interprets.\n\nThe problem is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` works with `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which are ref structs and can't be used in expression trees. When the compiler tries to build an expression tree using this method, it either fails to compile or fails at runtime because ref structs can't be boxed or represented in the expression tree interpreter.\n\nIn .NET 10, the compiler is likely now preferring `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over the `IEnumerable<T>` version when calling `Contains` on an array, which breaks expression tree scenarios that were previously working with the `Enumerable` version. Maybe the real issue is that .NET 10 changed how `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads are resolved, making `MemoryExtensions.Contains` the preferred choice for arrays over `Enumerable.Contains`, and since expression trees can't represent span-based operations, this causes a runtime failure when the expression tree tries to execute a method it can't actually represent. The issue is that expression tree lambdas have compiler support to reject constructs that can't be represented in trees, so if `Contains` now resolves to a span-based method, the compiler should catch this at compile time. But the user is reporting a runtime error, which suggests either they're building the tree manually instead of using lambda syntax, or the compiler is generating a valid tree with the wrong method reference that only fails when interpreted. Looking at their code, they're using the lambda syntax...\n\nThe solution would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to ensure the expression tree uses the LINQ method instead of the span-based one. But I'm puzzled by the \"throws at runtime\" description — that suggests the compiler isn't catching this as an error, which is odd if the method truly can't be represented in expression trees. The user might be imprecise about whether this is a compile-time or runtime issue, or there could be a specific scenario where it surfaces at runtime. Another angle: maybe .NET 10 added a new array-specific overload like `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this T[], T)` that wouldn't trigger a compile error in expression trees but could cause runtime issues if the expression interpreter doesn't recognize it. I'm also thinking about the well-documented breaking change around overload resolution preferring `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads that started in .NET 9 and continues into .NET 10.\n\nLooking at the exact code, in .NET 9 `array.Contains(num)` resolves to the `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` overload and works fine. But in .NET 10 with the new overload resolution rules, it might now try to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead, which would likely produce a compile error in an expression tree context.\n\nThe most likely scenario is that C# 14's improved overload resolution now prefers the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` overload over `Enumerable.Contains` when calling `.Contains()` on an array, but since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct that can't be used in expression trees, this causes a failure. The fix would be to explicitly cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use another disambiguation approach. I'm realizing the most likely explanation is that this manifests as a compile-time error in most cases, though the user might be perceiving it as a runtime issue depending on their build process or specific .NET version. The root cause is the same either way—it's about how the compiler handles method resolution in expression trees, particularly with the `params` keyword changes in newer C# versions. In C# 14, the compiler might now consider `MemoryExtensions.Contains` as a candidate due to changes in extension method resolution, but this would trigger a compile error since ref structs aren't allowed in expression trees. However, there's a possibility the compiler still selects `Enumerable.Contains` for the expression tree itself, and then at runtime with .NET 10's interpreter, something about how the method is invoked or resolved could cause a failure—perhaps due to a signature change or ambiguity in how the compiled expression executes.\n\nI should focus on the practical solution here: the root cause is that in .NET 10 and C# 14, `array.Contains(value)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, and since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct that expression trees can't represent, this breaks. The fixes are straightforward—either cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` before calling `Contains`, or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly.","outputTokens":4056,"requestId":"6C2D:1FF93E:BE3621:DE46F1:69FE8502"},"id":"68c105aa-a4e5-43c0-8d1e-4fad1d075108","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:52:34.138Z","parentId":"cd8a7a95-af99-4492-91c8-f1be4e97a01b"}
